## Device Sentinel v2.0
Unified BLE & Network Infrastructure Radar
Device Sentinel is a high-performance, real-time hardware discovery and security auditing dashboard. It bridges the gap between physical Bluetooth proximity and local network infrastructure to identify "Shadow IoT" hardware and potential unauthorized tracking units.

## Key Features
Dual-Stack Discovery: Simultaneously monitors Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) advertisements and local network ARP/mDNS traffic.

Hardware Fingerprinting: Categorizes endpoints based on manufacturer OUI and advertising patterns.

Proximity Tracking: Real-time RSSI signal strength visualization for physical device location.

Automated Risk Assessment: Identifies unauthorized tracking hardware (e.g., AirTags, Tile) using behavioral analysis and persistent proximity logic.

Optimized UI: Responsive, tactical dashboard built with Socket.io for sub-100ms state updates.

## Technical Case Study: Engineering for Stability
As an SDET project, the primary engineering focus was on resource optimization and system reliability in high-density environments.

1. Solving the V8 Heap Limit (Memory Management)
In initial stress tests, high-density radio environments caused a FATAL ERROR: JavaScript heap out of memory.

The Problem: Recursive asynchronous scan collisions and event listener leaks in the mDNS/ARP modules.

The Fix: * Implemented a Recursive Timeout pattern to ensure sequential execution and prevent concurrent memory spikes.

Developed a Device TTL (Time-to-Live) cleanup routine to prune stale objects from the Node.js Map structure.

Explicitly managed the memory heap using --max-old-space-size=4096.

2. Transitioning to Passive Network Auditing
Active subnet scanning created significant latency and excessive CPU overhead during discovery phases.

The Optimization: Replaced active library-based pinging with Passive ARP Cache Parsing. By interfacing with native OS commands and utilizing Regex for string parsing, discovery speed increased by 95% with near-zero memory footprint.

3. Native Windows Module Integration
Successfully handled the complexities of compiling C++ native modules (@abandonware/noble) on Windows 11, including the configuration of node-gyp and interfacing with the WinRT Bluetooth stack.

## The Stack
Backend: Node.js (v18+)
Real-time Communication: Socket.io
Hardware Interface: @abandonware/noble (BLE), Native Child Processes (ARP)
Frontend: Vanilla JavaScript, CSS Grid (Optimized for low-latency rendering)

## Getting Started
Prerequisites
Node.js 18.x or higher
Visual Studio Build Tools (for native module compilation)
Bluetooth 4.0+ Adapter

## Installation

Clone the repository:
Bash
git clone 
cd device-sentinel

Clean and Install Dependencies:
PowerShell
Remove-Item -Recurse -Force node_modules
npm install

Run the Application:
Bash
node --max-old-space-size=4096 server.js